{
  "Question": "<p>This is just for fun and inspired by <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/3866025/estimating-pi-using-only-2s/\">Estimating pi, using only 2s</a>.</p> <p>For a positive integer <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_143\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span>, let <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_144\"><math alttext=\"f(n)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> denote the minimum number of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_145\"><math alttext=\"2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>2</mn></semantics></math></span>s needed to express <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_146\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span> using addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and exponentiation, together with the ability to concatenate <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_147\"><math alttext=\"2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>2</mn></semantics></math></span>s, so for example <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_148\"><math alttext=\"2\\times 22^{2}+\\frac{222}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>\u00d7</mo><msup><mn>22</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>222</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span> is a valid expression. Other variants involving different sets of allowed operations are possible, of course. This function is very far from monotonic, so to smooth it out let's also consider</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_149\"><math alttext=\"g(n)=\\text{max}_{1\\leq m\\leq n}f(m).\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><msub><mtext>max</mtext><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>\u2264</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>\u2264</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>For example,</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_150\"><math alttext=\"f(1)=2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_151\"><math alttext=\"1=\\frac{2}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span>)</li> <li><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_152\"><math alttext=\"f(11)=3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>11</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_153\"><math alttext=\"11=\\frac{22}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>11</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span>)</li> </ul> <blockquote> <p><strong>Question:</strong> What can you say about <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_154\"><math alttext=\"f(n)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_155\"><math alttext=\"g(n)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>? Can you give exact values for small values of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_156\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span>? Can you give (asymptotic or exact) upper bounds? Lower bounds?</p> </blockquote> <p>As a simple example we can write any positive integer <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_157\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span> in the form <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_158\"><math alttext=\"2^{k}+n^{\\prime}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2032</mo></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_159\"><math alttext=\"n^{\\prime}&lt;2^{k}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2032</mo></msup><mo>&lt;</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span> (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_160\"><math alttext=\"2^{k}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi></msup></semantics></math></span> is just the leading digit in the binary expansion of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_161\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span>), which gives <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_162\"><math alttext=\"f(n)\\leq f(k)+1+f(n^{\\prime})\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>\u2264</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2032</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>. If we write <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_163\"><math alttext=\"\\ell(n)=\\lfloor\\log_{2}n\\rfloor\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">\u230a</mo><mrow><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">\u230b</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> then iterating this gives something like</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_164\"><math alttext=\"g(n)\\leq\\sum_{k=1}^{\\ell(n)}\\left(g(k)+1\\right).\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>\u2264</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msubsup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>This gives an upper bound growing something like <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_165\"><math alttext=\"\\ell(n)\\ell^{2}(n)\\ell^{3}(n)\\dots\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> which I think is pessimistic. For example, in my answer to the linked question I show that</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_166\"><math alttext=\"f(14885392687)\\leq 36\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>14885392687</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>\u2264</mo><mn>36</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_167\"><math alttext=\"\\ell(14885392687)=33\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2113</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>14885392687</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>33</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> so maybe we can expect something as good as <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_168\"><math alttext=\"g(n)=O(\\log n)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>O</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> for an upper bound. I have no idea about a lower bound, other than to write down an upper bound on the number of possible expressions that can be made with a given number of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_169\"><math alttext=\"2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>2</mn></semantics></math></span>s.</p> <p><strong>Edit:</strong> A related question involving <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_170\"><math alttext=\"4\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>4</mn></semantics></math></span>s and more allowed operations: <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/93729/how-many-fours-are-needed-to-represent-numbers-up-to-n\">How many fours are needed to represent numbers up to <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_171\"><math alttext=\"N\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>N</mi></semantics></math></span>?</a></p>",
  "Title": "What's the minimum number of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_142\"><math alttext=\"2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>2</mn></semantics></math></span>s needed to write a positive integer?",
  "Tags": "combinatorics,optimization,recreational-mathematics"
}